nd become dominant during the nineteenth century. The book examines the phenomenon of 1914 and the views held by people of that class, since it was under their leadership that the country went to war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary service, VoluntaryxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aBritish army.  aCharles Darwin.  aGerman.  aGreat War.  aKarl von Clausewitz.  aVictorian private solider.  acompulsory service.  afree trade.  aimperialism.  aliberal education.  aparliamentary reform.  apatriotism.  aupper middle class.  aupper-class intellectual culture.  avolunteers.1 aReader, W.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611950640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119506/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles